# The docstring is the contract

This test's docstring defines its scope: exactly what the test is meant to
verify. Your job is to make the test pass and make it verify exactly that scope
-- no more, no less. The docstring is authoritative: do NOT re-derive the
intended scope from the commands or the implementation. Read the docstring and
take it as given.

The docstring is READ-ONLY. Never edit it.

# If the test fails

You can record multiple kinds of changes -- they are not mutually exclusive (one
entry per kind, not per individual edit):

- "FIX_TEST": fix the test code (including fixtures).
- "FIX_IMPL": fix the program being tested.

Each change has a status: "SUCCEEDED" if the fix worked, or "FAILED" if you
tried but could not complete it. If you cannot determine what is wrong, report
no changes.

A status describes only whether *you* landed that change. Anything that needs
attention beyond your own test -- whether it stopped you or not -- goes in
"escalations" (see "# Escalations" below), which is a separate field. Never
water down a status to signal "someone should look at this".

When deciding whether to fix the test or the implementation, the docstring is the
arbiter: the correct behavior is whatever the docstring's scope says it should
be. If the implementation diverges from the documented scope, fix the
implementation; if the test asserts something outside the documented scope, fix
the test.

# If the test succeeds - or after you fixed a failing test

Make the test verify exactly its docstring scope -- check it in BOTH directions:

- Coverage (forward): is everything the scope calls for actually verified? If the
  scope says to observe a real effect (e.g. that a resumed workspace actually
  serves its `system_interface`, not merely that a route returned 200), the test
  must observe it. Add any missing verification the scope requires.

- Trace (backward): does every assertion trace back to the scope? An assertion
  that verifies something the scope does not mention is gold-plating: it adds
  brittleness without verifying documented behavior. REMOVE it.

A test that already verifies exactly its scope needs no change: leaving the
changes object empty is a correct, good outcome, NOT a failure. Do not add
assertions merely to be thorough -- the scope fixes what "thorough" means here.

Removing or simplifying an over-fitted assertion is a real improvement, exactly
as valuable as adding a missing one -- both are recorded under "IMPROVE_TEST".

You may add a separate pytest function for an unhappy/error path when the
docstring's scope includes that failure mode. Only do so when the scope calls for
it -- not to manufacture extra coverage.

If you make improvements (adding, removing, or restructuring), record a change
under the key "IMPROVE_TEST". If an improvement needs a larger-scale
intervention you cannot make here, leave it out of "changes" and raise an
escalation instead. If the test already verifies exactly its scope, leave the
changes object empty.

# Escalations

An escalation says "this needs attention beyond my test". It is INDEPENDENT of
whether your test passed and of every change's status: a clean pass can and
often should raise one. Escalating costs you nothing and is never counted as a
failure.

Raise an escalation in either of these two cases.

## Kind "BLOCKER": something stopped you

Many minds tests need infrastructure a single test cannot stand up: a Docker
daemon and a pre-baked workspace snapshot (`minds_snapshot_resume`), a deployed
Modal env (`minds_deployment` mints its own; `minds_services` needs a shared
one), or secrets (an `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, imbue_cloud login, Modal deploy
tokens, litellm keys). If the test skips or errors because such setup or a
secret is absent from THIS environment, that is a blocker, not something to hack
around locally. The same goes for a missing shared helper or a fixture that
mocks the wrong thing.

Do NOT paper over it with a brittle local hack. Instead leave a comment at the
relevant spot in the code, on its own line, in exactly this form:

  # FIXME(tmr): <one-line description of the shared setup change needed>

and raise an escalation with kind "BLOCKER".

## Kind "SHARED_PATTERN": your fix worked, but it is not really yours to make

This is the more common and more valuable case, and it is easy to miss.

Before you commit a fix, check whether it already exists nearby: grep the
sibling tests in the same file and directory for the change you are about to
make (the same marker, the same added decorator, the same rewritten line, the
same config key).

If two or more siblings already carry it, the problem is by definition NOT
specific to your test -- you are the Nth agent to apply the same patch by hand,
and the right fix is one shared change (a fixture, a conftest default, a config
value) that replaces all of them at once. You cannot make that change safely
from here, because you can only see one test.

So: apply your local fix as normal AND raise an escalation with kind
"SHARED_PATTERN", naming the sibling tests you found as evidence. Do not skip
the escalation just because your local fix worked.

If you catch yourself writing a justification like "matching the sibling tests"
or "as the other tests in this file do", that is this case. Escalate it.

## In both cases

Describe in detail_markdown what the shared change should be and which tests it
would cover. A later integration step collects these, resolves the ones it can
verify suite-wide, and surfaces the rest to the user. Your job is to flag them
clearly -- do not attempt the suite-wide change yourself.

# Examining the test output

After each test run, examine any output the test produced (logs, captured
stdout/stderr, workspace/service event files). Look for unexpected output such as
warnings, deprecation notices, or error messages that were not caught by the test
assertions. If you find something concerning, consider whether the test should
assert on it (only if the scope covers it), or whether the implementation should
be fixed to avoid the warning.

# Committing your changes

IMPORTANT: Each change kind MUST get its own separate commit. Changes of the same
kind should be combined in one commit. The commit message MUST start with the kind
in brackets. Examples:

  [FIX_TEST] Assert the resumed workspace serves system_interface
  [FIX_IMPL] Register the missing service in the events stream
  [IMPROVE_TEST] Remove assertion outside the documented scope

This means if you make both a FIX_TEST and a FIX_IMPL change, you should have
exactly two commits. Do NOT mix different kinds in the same commit.

Do NOT write a changelog entry, and ignore any repo instruction telling you to
add one. You are one of many agents whose commits are combined into a single
pull request; the integration step writes one unified changelog entry for the
whole run, fed by your summary_markdown.

Keep code comments proportionate: a line or two on *why* a non-obvious change
was needed. The full reasoning belongs in summary_markdown, not in the source.

# Running tests multiple times

You may run the test multiple times during your work (initial run, then after
each fix attempt). Before each run, decide on a brief description: "initial run"
for the first one, or something like "after fixing assertion timeout" for
subsequent runs. Record each run in the test_runs field of the outcome.

# Writing the result

Write the result atomically to avoid races with the orchestrator reading it:
1. First write to .test_output/{{ outcome_filename }}.draft (relative to the git repo root)
2. Then rename (mv) the .draft file to .test_output/{{ outcome_filename }}

The schema is:

{"changes": {"FIX_TEST": {"status": "SUCCEEDED", "summary_markdown": "Fixed assertion"}},
 "errored": false,
 "tests_passing_before": false,
 "tests_passing_after": true,
 "summary_markdown": "Fixed test assertion and verified it passes.",
 "test_runs": [
   {"run_name": "<try_1>", "description_markdown": "initial run"},
   {"run_name": "<try_2>", "description_markdown": "after fixing assertion timeout"}
 ],
 "escalations": [
   {"kind": "BLOCKER",
    "title": "minds_services suite needs a shared deployed Modal env",
    "detail_markdown": "The test skips because no shared services env exists in this run; a fixture or run-level env is needed rather than a per-test workaround."}
 ]}

Fields:
- changes: object keyed by change kind (IMPROVE_TEST, FIX_TEST, FIX_IMPL). Each
  value has status (SUCCEEDED or FAILED) and summary_markdown. One entry
  per kind -- do not duplicate kinds.
- errored: true only for infrastructure errors that prevented you from working.
- tests_passing_before: were tests passing before you made any changes?
- tests_passing_after: are tests passing now, after all your changes?
- summary_markdown: overall markdown summary of what happened.
- test_runs: list of objects, one per test run, in order. Each has run_name
  and description_markdown (brief description of what this run was for).
- escalations: list of objects, each with kind ("BLOCKER" or "SHARED_PATTERN"),
  title, and detail_markdown. Omit or use [] if you have none. This field is
  independent of every other field -- a passing test with no changes may still
  carry escalations.

# Publishing the outputs archive

After the outcome file is written, package the outputs and publish them
where the orchestrator can find them. Run this from the git repo root:

{{ publish_snippet }}

This MUST be the very last step. The orchestrator polls for outputs.tar.gz
and treats its appearance as the signal that you are done. The .tmp + rename
sequence prevents the orchestrator from reading a half-written archive. Omit
branch.bundle when you made no commits beyond the base branch.

# Important: do not ask for user input

For this initial request, do NOT ask the user for any input or clarification.
Work autonomously. If something is unclear or you are blocked, produce a result
with an escalation of kind "BLOCKER" explaining what you needed, and explain in
the summary_markdown. If the user sends follow-up messages later, you may ask them
questions at that point.
